If it's a story you want to write, then write it. there are several threads/generals you can share it in, including the writefag general.

Make a clear distinction in your plot, though. Genetic engineering isn't necessarily transformation. Genetic engineering is creating a new life form from a DNA code that has been manipulated. A new creature is born/hatched/whatever in a form its DNA programs it to take, however that DNA has been manipulated to express its code.

Transformation (from a hard science perspective) would be gene therapy, where you create some sort of serum with genes in it that you inject into a creature/human. Those genes then replace the existing genes in all of that creature's cells and force it to re-grow into a new form.

A true TF story I'd probably not discuss in /hmoha/ under most circumstances. It would be more appropriate in several other possible generals. I might mention it here once and point to another thread for discussion & feedback. However, depending on how you wrote it and how the plot resolved, it could potentially be /hmofa/ material. We won't really know until you write it and share it.

Anonymous Tue 22 Feb 2022 11:47:51 No.45720708 Report

>>45719040
Pulp is hardly benchmark for 'purple prose'. Not that is not there, but you'd need to go far more extreme than Lovecraft for the term to start to apply. For older authors books used to be the primary medium they focused on, describing shit was to properly set the scene and mood. Meanwhile modern authors tend to learn to write TV/movie scripts and sell them as books in the hopes they get big enough to be picked up. For them describing the scene in detail is a waste of time since it would interfere with the later adaptation process and something best left to an eventual director. I find that overly broad accusation of 'purple prose' come from people that want to divert attention from their own minimalist writing.

Anonymous Tue 22 Feb 2022 13:47:53 No.45721904 Report
Quoted By:
>>45720708
That's a bit reductive. You can definitely find good, classic literature that is also tightly written. Hemingway is pretty tight, for instance. Of Mice and Men is super tight. Grapes of Wrath is not, but not because it's purple. It just has a lot of fucking "telling" and is perhaps a bit more meticulous than it needs to be. Teaching over-description as poor craftsmanship is actually a major feature of The Elements of Style, which was written back in 1918, well before television was involved, and has been considered a major handbook since then. Detailed description is actually somewhat more accepted in literary circles now than it was when Elements of Style was released.

I strongly suspect that if you go back and read some of the books you were thinking of when you made this claim, you'll find they're actually way lighter on description than you remember. Your imagination does a lot of heavy lifting without all that much prompting, and you tend to remember a lot of that detail as part of the book when you think back on it. I say this as someone who is himself entirely too given to description in writing. Make no mistake, that is a weakness of mine.
